Part 1: Getting started [1.5 Marks]¶

We are going to work with a credit card fraud detection dataset, consisting of transactions made by credit cards in September 2013 by European cardholders. The dataset contains only numerical input variables (V1, V2, V28) which are the principal components obtained with PCA transformation (PCA will the introduced later in this course), due to confidentiality issues. The only features which have not been transformed with PCA are Time (seconds elapsed between each transaction and the first transaction in the dataset) and Amount (transaction Amount).\ This dataset contains 30 key features, which are not directly interpretable but contain meaningful information about the dataset. Load the dataset in CSV file using Pandas. The dataset is called creditcard.csv. Print out the first few columns of the dataset.

  • How many rows are there? 284807 [0.1]
  • Which column contains the targets? column 31 [0.1]
  • What is the meaning of target values? Whether the transaction is fraudulent [0.2]

It's important to know how many examples we have for each class when we work with a new dataset.

  • What is the percentage of entries in the dataset for each class? 99.83% is 0 and 0.17% is 1 [0.1]
  • Is this data considered balanced or unbalanced? Why is this the case? Heavily Unbalanced [0.1]
  • Why is balance/imbalance important? How might this class ditribution affect a KNN classifier for example, which we explored in Project 1? Inbalance can skew the bias of the model that we train. Since nearly all the data has an output 0, if we just trained a model to output 0, it would be 99.83% accurate!! If we used a knn classifier, it may be very hard for it to classify correctly, and it'd be difficult to find the optimized value for k.[0.5]
  • What metrics should we use to evaluate a model in such cases? Precision, Accuracy, F1 Score. [0.2]

Part 2: Single feature model with one Gaussian distribution: [2.5 Marks]¶

We'll start by making a prediction using a single feature of our dataset at a time.

Please note that we only use V features in our model.

a. Fitting regardless of class:

  1. Fit a single Gaussian distribution on a single feature of the full training dataset (both classes) using sklearn.mixture.GaussianMixture when n_components=1.
  2. Compute AUC (Area under the ROC Curve) based on sklearn.mixture.GaussianMixture.score_samples on both the full training set and validation set (including both classes).
  3. Repeat the above steps for each of the features and present your findings in a table.
  4. Find the best 3 features to distinguish fraud transactions from not-fraud transactions based on the AUC of the validation set. [0.2]
  5. Make a prediction based on a model's scores: If the score_samples is lower than a threshold, we consider that transaction as a fraud. Find an optimal threshold that maximizes the F1 Score of the validation set for each of those 3 features separately. (Do not check every possible value for threshold, come up with a faster way!) Compute F1 score using sklearn.metrics.f1_score. [0.5]
  6. Report the complexity of your method (Big O notation) for determining the optimal threshold.[0.5]

b. Fitting based on class:

  1. Pick 3 features that had the best AUC in Part 2a.
  2. Compute AUC and F1 score when you fit a Gaussian only on not-fraud transactions (instead of all the transactions).
  3. Compare your results from parts 2a and 2b (AUC and F1 score) in a table. [0.8]
  4. Are these results different or similar? Why?[0.5]

### Part A:
from sklearn.mixture import GaussianMixture
import numpy as np
from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score

# Create an empty DataFrame to store the results
results = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Feature', 'Training AUC', 'Validation AUC'])
feature_names = X_train.columns

# Loop through all features
for feature_name in feature_names:
    # Extract the single feature data
    X_train_feature = X_train[[feature_name]].values
    X_val_feature = X_val[[feature_name]].values

    #create and fit a GaussianMixture model
    gmm = GaussianMixture(n_components=1)
    gmm.fit(X_train_feature)

    #calculate the NEGATIVE loglikelihood scores for both training and validation sets
    train_log_likelihood = -gmm.score_samples(X_train_feature)
    val_log_likelihood = -gmm.score_samples(X_val_feature)
    train_auc = roc_auc_score(y_train, train_log_likelihood)
    val_auc = roc_auc_score(y_val, val_log_likelihood)

    results = results.append({'Feature': feature_name, 'Training AUC': train_auc, 'Validation AUC': val_auc}, ignore_index=True)

print(results)

from sklearn.metrics import f1_score

# Initialize dictionary to store the optimal threshold and F1 score for each feature
results_dict = {}

for feature_name in top_features['Feature']:

    # extract the training and val data for the current feature
    X_train_feature = X_train[[feature_name]].values
    X_val_feature = X_val[[feature_name]].values

    # fit the Gaussian mixture model using the training data for the current feature
    gmm = GaussianMixture(n_components=1) # use 1 component
    gmm.fit(X_train_feature)  # fit on the training set

    # get the log-likelihood scores
    val_log_likelihood = -gmm.score_samples(X_val_feature)

    # Initialize variables
    best_f1 = 0
    best_threshold = 0

    # iterate through a range of possible threshold values
    for threshold in np.linspace(val_log_likelihood.min(), val_log_likelihood.max(), 100):
        # Predict using the current threshold
        y_pred = val_log_likelihood < threshold
        current_f1 = f1_score(y_val, y_pred)

        # Update the best F1 Score and threshold if the new score is higher
        if current_f1 > best_f1:
            best_f1 = current_f1
            best_threshold = threshold

    results_dict[feature_name] = {'Optimal Threshold': best_threshold, 'Best F1 Score': best_f1}

# Print the optimal thresholds and F1 scores for each feature
for feature, result in results_dict.items():
    print(f"{feature}: Threshold = {result['Optimal Threshold']}, F1 Score = {result['Best F1 Score']}")

"""
Q6. Complexity:
Assuming that the number of features is irrelevant, for simply finding the optimal
threshold for any given feature, the complexity is O(n*k) where n is the number
of thresholds tested and k is the size of the validation set. This is because
we're looping through the thresholds, so there is a direct proportionality
to n, and for each threshold we must make a prediction and calculate the f1 scores,
which creates a direct proportionality to k. Therefor, complexity is on the order
of O(n*k)
"""

    # Compute the AUC for both training and validation sets
    train_auc = roc_auc_score(y_train, train_scores)
    val_auc = roc_auc_score(y_val, val_scores)

    # F1 Score calculation
    best_f1 = 0
    best_threshold = 0
    for threshold in np.linspace(val_scores.min(), val_scores.max(), 100):
        y_pred = (val_scores > threshold).astype(int)
        current_f1 = f1_score(y_val, y_pred)
        if current_f1 > best_f1:
            best_f1 = current_f1
            best_threshold = threshold

    results.append({
        'Feature Pair': pair,
        'Train AUC': train_auc,
        'Validation AUC': val_auc,
        'Best F1 Score': best_f1,
        'Best Threshold': best_threshold
    })

Part 4: Single feature model with two Gaussian distributions. [2 Marks]¶

Now we will use two different distributions for fraud and not-fraud transactions.

  1. Fit a Gaussian distribution ($G_1$) on a feature of not-fraud transactions using sklearn.mixture.GaussianMixture when n_components=1. [0.25]
  2. Fit another Gaussian distribution ($G_2$) on the same feature but for fraud transactions using sklearn.mixture.GaussianMixture when n_components=1. [0.25]
  3. Compute the score samples ($S$) for both $G_1$ and $G_2$ on the validation set to get $S_1$ and $S_2$, respectively. [0.25]
  4. Find an optimal $c$ (a real number) that maximizes validation set F1 Score for a model such that if $S_1 < c \times S_2$, the transaction is classified as an anomaly. For example, if $c=1$ we could say that if $S_2$ is greater than $S_1$, ($S_1$<$S_2$) then the transaction is an anomaly (the transaction belongs to the $G_2$ distribution which represents fraud transactions). For start consider $c$ in $[0,10]$ with steps of 0.1, you can change this window in your experiments if needed. [0.25]
  5. Repeat the steps above for all the features. What is the best F1 Score that you get for training and validation? Which feature and what c? [1]

from sklearn.mixture import GaussianMixture
import numpy as np
from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score
from sklearn.metrics import f1_score

#function to add a fitting strategy to a dataframe
def add_strategy_result(df, strategy_name, features, n_components_non_fraud,
                        n_components_fraud, training_auc, validation_auc, f1_score):
    new_entry = {
        'strategy_name': strategy_name,
        'features': ', '.join(features),  # Convert list of features to a comma-separated string
        'n_components_non_fraud': n_components_non_fraud,
        'n_components_fraud': n_components_fraud,
        'training_auc': training_auc,
        'validation_auc': validation_auc,
        'f1_score': f1_score
    }
    return df.append(new_entry, ignore_index=True)

#Initialize dataframe
results_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=[
    'strategy_name',
    'features',
    'n_components_non_fraud',
    'n_components_fraud',
    'training_auc',
    'validation_auc',
    'f1_score'
])

"""
After copying and pasting the same strategy 3 times over with different hyper-
parameters, I realized I should just make a robust function which takes my
choice of hyperparameters and gives me the outputs I need (for concision).
"""
def model_and_evaluate(X_train, y_train, X_val, y_val, features,
                       n_components_all=None, n_components_non_fraud=None,
                       n_components_fraud=None, fit_strategy='all'):

    #Initialize random_state for mixture model
    random_state = 0

    # Based on the strategy, fit the GMMs
    if fit_strategy == 'non-fraud':
        gmm = GaussianMixture(n_components=n_components_non_fraud, random_state=random_state)
        gmm.fit(X_train[y_train == 0][features])  # fit only on non-fraudulent data

        scores_train = -gmm.score_samples(X_train[features])
        scores_val = -gmm.score_samples(X_val[features])

    # Fit to all data
    elif fit_strategy == 'all':
        gmm = GaussianMixture(n_components=n_components_all, random_state=random_state)
        gmm.fit(X_train[features])  # fit on the entire dataset

        scores_train = -gmm.score_samples(X_train[features])
        scores_val = -gmm.score_samples(X_val[features])

    # Fit to fraud and non-fraud seperately
    elif fit_strategy == 'mixed':
        gmm_non_fraud = GaussianMixture(n_components=n_components_non_fraud, random_state=random_state)
        gmm_non_fraud.fit(X_train[y_train == 0][features])

        gmm_fraud = GaussianMixture(n_components=n_components_fraud, random_state=random_state)
        gmm_fraud.fit(X_train[y_train == 1][features])

        #Perform score subtraction between fraudulent and non-fraudulent data
        scores_train = gmm_fraud.score_samples(X_train[features]) - gmm_non_fraud.score_samples(X_train[features])
        scores_val = gmm_fraud.score_samples(X_val[features]) - gmm_non_fraud.score_samples(X_val[features])
    else:
        raise ValueError("Invalid fit strategy")

    #calculate AUC
    auc_train = roc_auc_score(y_train, scores_train)
    auc_val = roc_auc_score(y_val, scores_val)

    #determine optimized F1 Score
    best_threshold_gen = 0
    best_f1_gen = 0

    #Use a double loop: one that finds the general threshold range,
    #then another which searches around it with higher precision:

    # Loop 1 (general)
    for threshold in np.linspace(scores_val.min(),scores_val.max(),20):
        y_pred_val = (scores_val > threshold).astype(int)
        f1 = f1_score(y_val, y_pred_val)
        if f1 > best_f1_gen:
            best_f1_gen = f1
            best_threshold_gen = threshold

    best_f1 = best_f1_gen
    best_threshold = best_threshold_gen

    # Loop 2 (Precise)
    for threshold in np.arange(best_threshold_gen-5, best_threshold_gen+5, 0.1):
        y_pred_val = (scores_val > threshold).astype(int)
        f1 = f1_score(y_val, y_pred_val)
        if f1 > best_f1:
            best_f1 = f1
            best_threshold = threshold

    #If using the precise loop didnt help
    if best_f1_gen>best_f1:
      best_f1 = best_f1_gen
      best_threshold = best_threshold_gen

    return auc_train, auc_val, best_f1, best_threshold

Part 7: Is Gaussian the only useful distribution? [1 Mark]¶

Search for other distributions that could be used to model the data. How popular are they? Is there a specific situation where a distribution works better? How can we find a suitable distribution to model our data? Do not forget to include your references.

"""
Some other distributions I found:
Poisson distribution, Exponential distribution, and gamma distribution.

The Poisson distribution is a discrete probability distribution that models the
number of events occurring in a fixed interval of time or space. It is particularly
useful when these events happen at a constant mean rate and independently of the
time since the last event. Poisson distributions are particularily useful for
counting statistics. The single parameter, lambda, represents the average
number of events in the specified interval. The Poisson distribution is frequently
used in many fields including telecommunications, astronomy, and finance. For
instance, it can be used to model the number of phone calls received by a call
center in an hour, or if you're the statistician Ladislaus Bortkiewicz in the
1800s, you can use it to analyze the average number of times, per year, a single
corps of the prussian army would experience a death of one of their members by
horse kick.

Ref:
Poisson Distributions | Definition, Formula & Examples, Scribbr, May 13, 2022 by Shaun Turney
https://www.scribbr.com/statistics/poisson-distribution/#:~:text=You%20can%20use%20a%20Poisson,days%20or%205%20square%20inches.

The exponential distribution is a continuous probability distribution that
describes the time between events in a process where events occur continuously
at a constant average rate. It is memoryless, meaning the past
events do not affect future events. Mathematically, its only parameter is , similar
to the poisson distribution, which is the rate at which events occur. The
exponential distribution is often used in reliability analysis and survival
studies, for instance, in modeling the time between failures of electronic
components, or the number of earthquakes in a year.

Ref:
Exponential Distribution: Uses, Parameters & Examples, Statistics by Jim, Jim Frost
https://statisticsbyjim.com/probability/exponential-distribution/

The Gamma distribution is a right-skewed distribution, similar to exponential,
which can be used to model the rates of independant events. While it is related
to the exponential and Chi-squared distributions, it's more general. The gamma
distribution models the time required for a certain number of events to occur,
making it a wait time between Poisson-distributed events. The two parameters,
alpha and beta, allow the distribution to take various shapes. In some
special cases, it reduces to the exponential distribution. It's frequently used
in fields like queuing models, climatology, and financial services to model various phenomena.

Ref:
Gamma Distribution: Uses, Parameters & Examples, Statistics by Jim, Jim Frost
https://statisticsbyjim.com/probability/gamma-distribution/

At the end of the day, the distribution you may use for modelling depends on
the type of data aswell as the natural shape of said data. If the data is categorized
by the time or space between independant events, then these other distributions
may function well, and the gamma or exponential may work especially for skewed,
a-symmetric statistical systems.
